{{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Al Masry Club Stadium | native_name = ستاد النادي المصري | image = | location = Al Manakh, [[Port Said]], Egypt | name = Al Masry Club Stadium | owner = [[Al-Masry SC]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://almasryclub.com/?p=4816 |title=محطات مهمة في تاريخ ستاد الدوري المصري |trans-title=History of Al Masry Club Stadium |language=Arabic |work=[[Al-Masry SC|Al Masry]] online |date=10 February 2018 |accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref> | operator = [[Al-Masry SC]] | opened = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1955|10|16}} | surface = Grass | tenants = [[Al-Masry SC]] | seating_capacity = 18,000 }}
'''Al Masry Club Stadium''' ({{Lang-arz|ستاد النادي المصري}}), formerly known as '''Port Said Stadium''' ({{Lang-arz|ستاد بور سعيد}}), is a multi-use all-seated [[stadium]] in Al Manakh, [[Port Said]], Egypt, which opened in 1955 and inaugurated by [[Hussein el-Shafei|Hussein El Shafei]], the Egyptian minister of social affairs on behalf of [[Gamal Abdel Nasser|President Gamal Abdel Nasser]].
Al Masry Club Stadium is owned by [[Al-Masry SC|Al Masry Sporting Club]], and has a capacity of 18,000. The stadium was banned from all activities on 1 February 2012 after the incidents of [[Port Said Stadium riot]] occurred following a [[2011–12 Egyptian Premier League|league match]] between Al Masry and [[Al Ahly SC|Al Ahly]] which resulted in the death 72 Al Ahly fans, 1 Al Masry fan and 1 police officer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/in-pictures-jubilation-in-cairo-riots-in-port-said-8468133.html?action=gallery&ino=4|title=In pictures: Jubilation in Cairo, riots in Port Said|date=26 January 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2095046/Egypt-riots-Fans-dead-Al-Ahly-lose.html|title=At least 74 fans killed as riots break out in Egypt following shock result|date=2 February 2012|publisher=}}</ref> The [[Egyptian Football Association]] suspended all football related activities immediately following that disaster. On 10 February 2018, after more than 6 years since the disaster, [[Association football|football]] activities returned to the stadium as Al Masry played against [[Zambia]]n team [[Green Buffaloes F.C.|Green Buffaloes]] in the [[2018 CAF Confederation Cup qualifying rounds|preliminary qualifying round]] of the [[2018 CAF Confederation Cup]].
The stadium also hosted some matches in [[1997 FIFA U-17 World Championship]], [[2006 Africa Cup of Nations]], [[Football at the 2007 Pan Arab Games|2007 Pan Arab Games Football Tournament]] and [[2009 FIFA U-20 World Cup]].
