{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = Cattle Market Ground | nickname = | country = England | image = | location = [[Islington]], [[London]] | establishment = 1863 | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year4 = 1867 | club4 = [[Gentlemen of the South]] | year3 = 1865 | club3 = Gentlemen of Middlesex | year2 = 1864 | club2 = [[South of England cricket team|South]] | year1 = 1864-1868 | club1 = [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]] | date = 3 September | year = 2010 | source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/550.html profile }}
'''Cattle Market Ground''' was a [[cricket]] ground in [[Islington]], [[London]] (formerly [[Middlesex]]). The first recorded match on the ground was in 1863, when Middlesex Clubs played a United England Eleven.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/550_misc.html Other matches played on Cattle Market Ground]</ref>
In 1864, the ground held its first [[first-class cricket|first-class]] match when [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]] played [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]]. From 1864 to 1868, the ground played host to 16 first-class matches involving Middlesex, the last of which saw them play [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]]. The ground also held first-class matches for the [[South of England cricket team|South]] in 1864, Gentlemen of Middlesex in 1865 and the [[Gentlemen of the South]] in 1867.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/550_f.html First-Class Matches played on Cattle Market Ground]</ref>
The last recorded match held on the ground came in September 1868 when the Gentlemen of Middlesex played the Australian Aboriginals during [[Australian Aboriginal cricket team in England in 1868|their tour of England]]. The ground closed when the owner of the hotel whose pitch it was decided to sell the land for development.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/england/content/ground/57070.html#Profile Ground profile]</ref> The hotel itself was situated next to the [[Metropolitan Cattle Market]], although its exact placing is unknown.
