{{unreferenced|date=February 2016}} {{About|the Japanese professional baseball hall of fame|baseball hall of fame organizations in other countries|Baseball Hall of Fame (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox Museum |name = Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame |image = Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum 20070317.jpg |imagesize = 300 |caption = |map_type = |map_caption = |coordinates = {{coord|35.705658|139.751914|display=inline}} |established = [[1959 in sports#Baseball|1959]] |dissolved = |location = [[Tokyo Dome]], Bunkyo Ward of [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]] |type = [[Professional sports]] [[hall of fame]] |visitors = |director = Norio Ichino |curator = |publictransit = |website = [http://english.baseball-museum.or.jp english.baseball-museum.or.jp] }} The {{nihongo|'''Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum'''|野球体育博物館|Yakyū Taiiku Hakubutsukan}} is a museum which includes a library, reference rooms and {{nihongo|Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame|野球殿堂|Yakyū Dendō}}.
It first opened in 1959 next door to [[Korakuen Stadium]] in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. In 1988, the museum moved to a new site within the [[Tokyo Dome]].
The Hall of Fame and Museum was created as a means to contribute to the development of baseball in Japan through dedication of baseball greats—players, executives, and [[umpire (baseball)|umpires]]—as Hall of Famers. In addition, the facility houses many memorable baseball materials including various kinds of baseball literature.
